return A.Q(A.HV(A.aGk(),new A.r2(1,"UNIT 1 \u2013 HISTORICAL BACKGROUND OF THE INDIAN CONSTITUTION\n\nThis unit explains how the modern constitutional system of India gradually developed through British rule and legislative reforms, ultimately leading to the adoption of the Constitution of India. The Indian Constitution did not emerge suddenly in 1950. It evolved through a long historical process shaped by colonial governance, administrative experiments, political demands, and constitutional developments. Each Act passed by the British Parliament introduced new administrative mechanisms, legislative institutions, and governance principles. These gradually transformed India from a trading colony into a constitutional democracy. Therefore, understanding the historical background is essential to understand why the Constitution contains features such as federalism, parliamentary government, judicial review, and fundamental rights.\n________________________________________\nIntroduction to Constitutional Development in India\nThe constitutional development of India began with the establishment of the East India Company. Initially, the Company entered India only for trade. However, over time, it began acquiring political control over territories. As the Company\u2019s power increased, the British Parliament became concerned about mismanagement, corruption, and lack of accountability. This led to the enactment of several laws to regulate administration in India. These laws gradually introduced centralized governance, legislative councils, representation, and responsible government.\nThe evolution of constitutional governance in India can be divided into three phases. The first phase involved Company rule from 1773 to 1858. The second phase involved Crown rule from 1858 to 1947. The third phase involved the framing of the Constitution by the Constituent Assembly. Each phase contributed important constitutional principles.\nFor example, centralized administration began with the Regulating Act. Legislative councils were introduced under Indian Councils Acts. Federal structure emerged under the Government of India Act 1935. Responsible government developed gradually through reforms. Thus, the present Constitution is the result of historical evolution rather than sudden creation.\n________________________________________\nEast India Company Rule in India\nThe East India Company was established in 1600 by a royal charter granted by Queen Elizabeth I. Initially, the Company functioned as a trading body. It set up trading factories in Surat, Bombay, Madras, and Calcutta. Over time, the Company expanded its influence through wars and treaties. The Battle of Plassey in 1757 and the Battle of Buxar in 1764 strengthened the Company's political control in India. After these victories, the Company obtained Diwani rights in Bengal, Bihar, and Orissa. This meant the Company gained the power to collect revenue and administer civil justice.\nHowever, the Company was not prepared to govern a large territory. Its administration was corrupt and inefficient. Officials exploited resources for personal gain. There was no clear separation between commercial and political functions. The Company\u2019s servants accumulated wealth while the local population suffered. The Bengal famine of 1770 exposed administrative failures. These conditions forced the British Parliament to intervene.\nThe British government realized that a private trading company controlling large territories was dangerous. Therefore, Parliament enacted laws to regulate the Company\u2019s administration. This marked the beginning of constitutional development in India.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nThe Company originally came to India to trade spices and textiles. But after gaining revenue powers in Bengal, it started governing people. However, since it was still a trading body, governance became secondary. Officials focused on profit rather than welfare. This created confusion and exploitation. Therefore, Parliament stepped in to regulate administration.\n________________________________________\nRegulating Act, 1773\nThe Regulating Act of 1773 was the first step taken by the British Parliament to regulate the administration of India. It marked the beginning of parliamentary control over the East India Company. The Act aimed to control corruption, improve administration, and centralize authority.\nBefore this Act, the presidencies of Bengal, Bombay, and Madras functioned independently. This created administrative inconsistency. The Regulating Act centralized power by designating the Governor of Bengal as the Governor-General of Bengal. Warren Hastings became the first Governor-General. The Governors of Bombay and Madras were made subordinate to the Governor-General. This introduced centralized administration for the first time.\nThe Act also created an Executive Council of four members to assist the Governor-General. Decisions were taken by majority vote. This introduced a collective decision-making process. However, the Governor-General could be outvoted by council members, creating administrative conflicts.\nAnother important feature of the Act was the establishment of the Supreme Court at Calcutta in 1774. The court consisted of a Chief Justice and three judges appointed by the Crown. The Supreme Court had jurisdiction over British subjects and certain civil matters. This marked the beginning of a judicial system in India.\nThe Act also prohibited Company officials from engaging in private trade and accepting gifts. This aimed to reduce corruption. The Company was required to submit reports to the British government. Thus, parliamentary supervision increased.\nDespite its importance, the Regulating Act had several defects. The powers of the Governor-General and Supreme Court were not clearly defined. This led to conflicts between executive and judiciary. The Supreme Court attempted to exercise jurisdiction over Indians, causing confusion. The Governor-General lacked effective control over subordinate presidencies.\nHowever, the Regulating Act was significant because it introduced centralized administration, parliamentary control, and judicial institutions. It marked the beginning of constitutional governance in India.\n________________________________________\nExample\nBefore 1773, Bombay Presidency could take decisions independently. After the Regulating Act, Bombay had to follow directions from the Governor-General of Bengal. This shows the beginning of centralized governance.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nIf three presidencies function independently, policies differ. But if one authority controls all, uniform administration develops. The Regulating Act created this central authority.\n________________________________________\nCase Law \u2013 Nand Kumar Case (1775)\nThe conflict between Supreme Court and executive became evident in the Nand Kumar case. Maharaja Nand Kumar accused Warren Hastings of corruption. Subsequently, Nand Kumar was tried by the Supreme Court for forgery and sentenced to death. This created controversy because the Supreme Court applied English law to an Indian. The case highlighted jurisdictional confusion between judiciary and executive.\nSignificance:\nThis case exposed defects in the Regulating Act and showed the need for clearer distribution of powers.\n________________________________________\nPitt\u2019s India Act, 1784\nThe Regulating Act of 1773 introduced parliamentary control over the East India Company, but it failed to create an effective administrative structure. Conflicts arose between the Governor-General and his Council, and between the Supreme Court and executive authorities. The British Parliament realized that stronger control was required. As a result, Pitt\u2019s India Act of 1784 was enacted to correct the defects of the Regulating Act. This Act introduced a system of dual control and strengthened British government supervision over Indian administration.\nThe most important feature of Pitt\u2019s India Act was the establishment of the Board of Control. This Board consisted of British government officials, including the Secretary of State and Chancellor of the Exchequer. The Board was responsible for supervising political affairs of the East India Company. While the Court of Directors continued to manage commercial activities, the British government controlled political administration. This created a system of dual government \u2014 commercial authority remained with the Company, while political authority shifted to the British government.\nThe Act also strengthened the position of the Governor-General. The Governor-General was given authority over the presidencies of Bombay and Madras in matters of war, diplomacy, and revenue. This further centralized power. The number of council members was reduced to three, making decision-making easier. The Act also required the Company to submit all communications related to civil, military, and revenue matters to the British government. This ensured effective parliamentary control.\nAnother important aspect of the Act was that it distinguished between political and commercial functions. Earlier, the Company exercised both without clear separation. Pitt\u2019s India Act separated governance from trade. This marked a shift from purely commercial rule to administrative governance.\nThe significance of Pitt\u2019s India Act lies in the fact that it established British government control over Indian administration while retaining the Company as an administrative agent. It strengthened centralized authority, improved supervision, and laid the foundation for future constitutional reforms.\n________________________________________\nExample\nBefore Pitt\u2019s India Act, the East India Company independently made political decisions such as war and treaties. After the Act, such decisions required approval of the Board of Control. This ensured that British government supervised Indian administration.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nThe Company became like a manager, while the British government became the owner. The Company executed administration, but the British government controlled policy decisions. This is called dual control.\n________________________________________\nCharter Act, 1813\nThe Charter Act of 1813 marked another important stage in constitutional development. The East India Company\u2019s charter was renewed every 20 years by Parliament. During renewal in 1813, Parliament introduced major changes. The most important change was the abolition of the Company\u2019s monopoly over trade with India. Until this Act, the Company had exclusive trading rights. The Charter Act opened Indian trade to private British merchants. However, the Company retained monopoly over trade with China and tea.\nThis Act also marked the beginning of British responsibility toward education in India. It provided that the British government should spend one lakh rupees annually for promotion of education and knowledge. This was the first time education became a state responsibility. Though implementation was limited, it laid the foundation for modern education policy.\nAnother feature of the Act was permission to Christian missionaries to enter India. Missionaries were allowed to promote education and religious activities. This contributed to social reform and spread of western education. However, it also created cultural conflicts in some regions.\nThe Charter Act of 1813 also emphasized that sovereignty over Indian territories rested with the British Crown. Though the Company administered India, ultimate authority belonged to the Crown. This clarified the political status of India under British rule.\nThe Act did not introduce major administrative changes, but it marked a shift in policy. The Company\u2019s commercial role declined and administrative role increased. The British government began to view India as a territory requiring governance rather than mere trade.\n________________________________________\nExample\nBefore 1813, only the East India Company could trade in Indian goods. After the Act, private British traders could also trade in India. This opened Indian markets to British merchants.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nImagine one company controlling all trade. Prices remain fixed and competition is absent. When trade opens to others, competition increases. The Charter Act 1813 introduced this competition.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nThe Charter Act 1813 is important because it:\n\u2022 Ended Company\u2019s trade monopoly \n\u2022 Introduced education responsibility \n\u2022 Allowed missionary activities \n\u2022 Recognized Crown sovereignty \n\u2022 Reduced commercial character of Company rule \nThis Act marked the gradual transition from commercial administration to governmental administration.\n________________________________________\nCharter Act, 1833\nThe Charter Act of 1833 is considered one of the most important constitutional developments during the East India Company rule. This Act transformed the Company from a commercial organization into a purely administrative body. It centralized legislative power and introduced administrative reforms which later influenced the structure of the Indian Constitution.\nOne of the most significant changes introduced by the Charter Act of 1833 was the designation of the Governor-General of Bengal as the Governor-General of India. Lord William Bentinck became the first Governor-General of India. This change centralized authority in India and ended the administrative independence of Bombay and Madras presidencies. The Governor-General of India now had complete legislative authority over the entire country. This was the beginning of legislative centralization.\nThe Act also created a centralized legislative council. The Governor-General\u2019s council was given power to legislate for all territories in India. The laws made by this council were called Acts instead of Regulations. This created a uniform legislative framework for India. This central legislative authority resembles the present Parliament\u2019s power to legislate for the entire country.\nAnother important feature of this Act was the abolition of the East India Company\u2019s commercial activities. The Company ceased to be a trading body and became purely administrative. This marked the complete transformation of the Company from a commercial enterprise into a political authority. The Company now governed India on behalf of the British Crown.\nThe Charter Act of 1833 also introduced the concept of open competition for civil services. It stated that Indians should not be disqualified from holding public offices on grounds of religion, race, or place of birth. This provision was significant because it recognized equality in public employment. However, in practice, competitive examinations were conducted in England, making it difficult for Indians to participate.\nThe Act also created the office of Law Member in the Governor-General\u2019s Council. Thomas Babington Macaulay became the first Law Member. He played a major role in codification of Indian laws. The Indian Penal Code and other codifications emerged from this period. This contributed to uniform legal system in India.\n________________________________________\nExample\nBefore the Charter Act 1833, Bombay and Madras presidencies could make their own laws. After this Act, only the Governor-General of India had legislative power. This centralized law-making authority.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nIf three different regions make separate laws, confusion arises. But if one authority makes laws for all, uniformity is maintained. The Charter Act 1833 introduced this uniform legislative system.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nThe Charter Act 1833 is important because:\n\u2022 It centralized legislative power \n\u2022 Created Governor-General of India \n\u2022 Abolished Company\u2019s trade functions \n\u2022 Introduced open civil services concept \n\u2022 Began codification of laws \n\u2022 Created uniform legislative authority \nThis Act laid foundation for centralized legislative governance in India.\n________________________________________\nCharter Act, 1853\nThe Charter Act of 1853 was the last Charter Act passed by the British Parliament. Unlike earlier Charter Acts, it did not renew the Company\u2019s rule for a fixed period. This indicated that the British Parliament intended to reconsider governance in India. The Act introduced significant administrative and legislative reforms.\nOne of the most important features of the Charter Act 1853 was the separation of legislative and executive functions of the Governor-General\u2019s Council. Previously, the council performed both executive and legislative functions. The Act created a separate legislative council by adding six new members. This marked the beginning of a legislative body similar to modern legislature.\nThe Act also introduced open competition for civil services. The recruitment to civil services was based on merit through competitive examinations. This allowed Indians to participate theoretically. This reform introduced merit-based bureaucracy. Later, this system became the basis of modern civil services.\nAnother important feature was expansion of legislative council. The Act added representatives from Bombay, Madras, Bengal, and North-Western provinces. This introduced regional representation. Though these members were not elected, their inclusion increased participation in law-making.\nThe Charter Act 1853 also allowed the legislative council to discuss laws in detail. This introduced deliberative legislative process. Members could debate and amend proposals. This resembled parliamentary legislative procedure.\nThe Act also indicated that the East India Company\u2019s administrative role was temporary. Parliament retained power to decide future governance. This eventually led to abolition of Company rule in 1858.\n________________________________________\nExample\nBefore 1853, the same council handled administration and law-making. After 1853, separate legislative members were added. This created a body similar to legislature.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nWhen one body both executes and makes laws, power concentrates. But when legislative members are added, debate increases. The Charter Act 1853 introduced this separation.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nThe Charter Act 1853 is important because:\n\u2022 It separated executive and legislative functions \n\u2022 Introduced competitive civil services \n\u2022 Expanded legislative council \n\u2022 Introduced representation \n\u2022 Created deliberative legislative procedure \nThis Act marked the transition toward representative legislative institutions.\n________________________________________\nGovernment of India Act, 1858\nThe Revolt of 1857 marked a turning point in the constitutional history of India. The revolt exposed the weaknesses of the East India Company\u2019s administration. The British Parliament concluded that a commercial organization was not suitable to govern a vast territory like India. As a result, the Government of India Act, 1858 was enacted. This Act abolished the rule of the East India Company and transferred the administration of India directly to the British Crown. Thus, Company rule ended and Crown rule began.\nUnder this Act, the Governor-General of India became the Viceroy representing the British Crown. Lord Canning became the first Viceroy of India. The title \u201cViceroy\u201d signified that the Governor-General acted as a representative of the Crown. This change symbolized the transfer of authority from a private company to the British monarchy.\nThe Act also created the office of the Secretary of State for India. This was a powerful position in the British government. The Secretary of State was assisted by a Council of India consisting of fifteen members. This council advised the Secretary of State in matters relating to Indian administration. The Secretary of State exercised complete control over Indian governance. He could send orders directly to India.\nAnother important feature of the Act was centralization of administration. The Viceroy and Secretary of State exercised strong control over provinces. The Act did not introduce representation or responsible government. It strengthened executive authority. Indian participation in governance remained minimal.\nThe Government of India Act 1858 also introduced the policy of non-interference in religious matters. The British government promised to respect Indian customs and traditions. It also assured equal treatment under law. These assurances were intended to prevent further revolts.\nThe significance of the Government of India Act 1858 lies in the transfer of power from Company to Crown. It introduced centralized executive authority, established Secretary of State, and marked the beginning of direct British rule.\n________________________________________\nExample\nBefore 1858, India was governed by the East India Company. After the Act, India was governed by the British Crown. This shows the shift from private rule to government rule.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nIf a private company runs a country, profit becomes priority. But when a government takes control, administration becomes more structured. The Act of 1858 brought this change.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nThe Government of India Act 1858:\n\u2022 Ended East India Company rule \n\u2022 Introduced Crown rule \n\u2022 Created Secretary of State for India \n\u2022 Introduced Viceroy \n\u2022 Centralized administration \n\u2022 Began direct British governance \nThis Act marked the beginning of modern administrative control in India.\n________________________________________\nIndian Councils Act, 1861\nThe Government of India Act 1858 centralized administration but did not involve Indians in governance. The British government realized that some participation was necessary. The Indian Councils Act 1861 introduced limited Indian participation and legislative decentralization.\nOne of the most important features of this Act was restoration of legislative powers to Bombay and Madras presidencies. Earlier, legislative authority was centralized. The Act allowed provinces to make laws for local matters. This marked the beginning of decentralization.\nThe Act also introduced legislative councils. The Governor-General\u2019s council was expanded by adding non-official members. Indians were nominated to the council for the first time. Lord Canning nominated Raja of Benaras and Maharaja of Patiala. This marked the beginning of Indian participation in law-making.\nAnother important feature was introduction of portfolio system. Under this system, different departments were assigned to different council members. This improved administrative efficiency. This system resembles the modern cabinet system where ministers handle departments.\nThe Act also gave ordinance-making power to the Governor-General. In emergencies, the Governor-General could issue ordinances without legislative approval. This resembles ordinance power under Article 123 of the Constitution.\nThe Indian Councils Act 1861 also recognized legislative decentralization. Provinces were allowed to legislate on local matters. This was the beginning of federal tendencies in Indian administration.\nHowever, Indian participation remained limited. Members were nominated and had no real power. They could not control executive authority. Despite limitations, the Act introduced representative institutions.\n________________________________________\nExample\nBefore 1861, no Indian participated in law-making. After this Act, Indians were nominated to legislative councils. This introduced limited participation.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nIf only rulers make laws, people\u2019s voice is absent. When representatives are included, governance becomes participatory. The Indian Councils Act 1861 introduced this participation.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nThe Indian Councils Act 1861:\n\u2022 Introduced Indian participation \n\u2022 Restored legislative powers to provinces \n\u2022 Introduced legislative councils \n\u2022 Created portfolio system \n\u2022 Gave ordinance power \n\u2022 Began decentralization \nThis Act marked the beginning of representative governance in India.\n________________________________________\nIndian Councils Act, 1892\nThe Indian Councils Act 1861 introduced Indian participation, but it was very limited. Indians were only nominated and had no real legislative power. As political awareness increased and the Indian National Congress began demanding reforms, the British government introduced further changes through the Indian Councils Act 1892. This Act slightly expanded legislative councils and increased Indian participation, though still in a limited manner.\nOne of the major features of the Indian Councils Act 1892 was the expansion of legislative councils. The number of members in both central and provincial legislative councils was increased. This allowed greater representation of Indians. Though members were still nominated, the Act introduced indirect election. Local bodies such as municipalities, universities, and district boards recommended members. The government then nominated them. This marked the beginning of electoral representation.\nAnother important feature was the right of members to discuss the budget. Members could ask questions and discuss financial matters. However, they were not allowed to vote on the budget. They also could not introduce supplementary questions. Thus, the power given was limited but significant.\nThe Act also increased Indian participation in governance. More Indians were included in legislative councils. Though they had limited authority, they could express public opinion. This created political awareness and encouraged constitutional development.\nHowever, the Indian Councils Act 1892 had several limitations. Members could not vote on laws. Executive authority remained dominant. The election system was indirect and controlled by the government. Responsible government was not introduced. Despite these limitations, the Act marked an important step toward representative governance.\n________________________________________\nExample\nA university could recommend a representative to the legislative council. The government would nominate that person. This was indirect election.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nIf people choose representatives directly, it is democracy. If organizations recommend representatives, it is indirect representation. The Indian Councils Act 1892 introduced this indirect system.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nThe Indian Councils Act 1892:\n\u2022 Expanded legislative councils \n\u2022 Introduced indirect election \n\u2022 Allowed budget discussion \n\u2022 Increased Indian participation \n\u2022 Began representative institutions \nThis Act marked the gradual development toward legislative representation.\n________________________________________\nMorley\u2013Minto Reforms, 1909 (Indian Councils Act 1909)\nThe Indian Councils Act 1909, also known as Morley\u2013Minto Reforms, introduced significant constitutional changes. These reforms were named after Lord Morley, Secretary of State for India, and Lord Minto, Viceroy of India. The reforms aimed to increase Indian participation in governance and respond to political demands.\nOne of the most important features of the Morley\u2013Minto Reforms was the expansion of legislative councils. The number of members in central and provincial councils was increased substantially. For the first time, some members were elected. This introduced the principle of election in Indian constitutional development.\nAnother important feature was the inclusion of Indians in executive councils. Satyendra Prasad Sinha became the first Indian member of the Viceroy\u2019s Executive Council. This marked the beginning of Indian participation in executive governance.\nThe most controversial feature of the Morley\u2013Minto Reforms was the introduction of separate electorates for Muslims. Under this system, Muslims elected their own representatives. This meant only Muslim voters could elect Muslim members. This introduced communal representation. The British government justified this as protection of minority interests.\nMembers of legislative councils were given the right to discuss budget and move resolutions. Though executive authority remained dominant, members could debate public issues. This increased legislative activity.\nHowever, responsible government was still absent. The executive remained accountable to the British government, not the legislature. Separate electorates created communal divisions. Despite limitations, the reforms expanded representation.\n________________________________________\nExample\nUnder separate electorates, Muslim voters elected Muslim representatives. Non-Muslims could not vote for those seats. This divided the electorate.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nIf voters are divided based on religion, political unity weakens. Separate electorates introduced such division.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nThe Morley\u2013Minto Reforms 1909:\n\u2022 Expanded legislative councils \n\u2022 Introduced elections \n\u2022 Included Indians in executive councils \n\u2022 Introduced separate electorates \n\u2022 Increased legislative participation \nThese reforms marked an important step toward representative government but also introduced communal politics.\n________________________________________\nBackground of Government of India Act, 1919\nAfter the Morley\u2013Minto Reforms of 1909, Indian political leaders demanded further constitutional reforms. The First World War also influenced British policy. The British government promised gradual development of self-governing institutions in India. In 1917, the Secretary of State for India, Edwin Montagu, announced that the objective of British policy was to introduce responsible government in India. Based on this declaration, the Montagu\u2013Chelmsford Reforms were introduced, leading to the Government of India Act, 1919.\nThe Government of India Act 1919 marked a significant step toward responsible government. It introduced constitutional reforms at both central and provincial levels. The Act expanded legislative councils, introduced bicameralism at the centre, increased Indian participation, and introduced the system of dyarchy in provinces.\n________________________________________\nBicameral Legislature at the Centre\nOne of the major features of the Government of India Act 1919 was the introduction of bicameral legislature at the centre. The central legislature consisted of two houses \u2014 Council of State and Legislative Assembly. The Council of State functioned as the upper house, while the Legislative Assembly functioned as the lower house. This was the beginning of bicameralism in India.\nMembers of both houses were partly elected and partly nominated. This introduced electoral representation. The legislature could discuss budget and pass laws. However, the Governor-General retained overriding powers. He could veto bills and issue ordinances. Therefore, the legislature did not have full authority.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nTwo houses were created similar to modern Parliament:\nUpper House \u2192 Council of State\nLower House \u2192 Legislative Assembly\nThis system later influenced:\nRajya Sabha \u2192 Upper House\nLok Sabha \u2192 Lower House\n________________________________________\nDyarchy in Provinces\nThe most important feature of the Government of India Act 1919 was the introduction of dyarchy in provinces. Dyarchy means dual government. Under this system, provincial subjects were divided into two categories \u2014 reserved subjects and transferred subjects.\nReserved subjects were administered by the Governor and his executive council. These subjects included police, finance, revenue, and law and order. These were important areas of administration. The Governor was not responsible to the legislature in these matters.\nTransferred subjects were administered by Indian ministers responsible to legislative councils. These subjects included education, public health, agriculture, and local government. Ministers were accountable to the legislature. This introduced partial responsible government.\nThus, administration in provinces was divided between British officials and Indian ministers. This system aimed to train Indians in governance.\n________________________________________\nExample\nEducation \u2192 transferred subject \u2192 Indian minister handled\nPolice \u2192 reserved subject \u2192 Governor handled\nThis shows division of power.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nImagine a government where important departments are kept by one authority and less important departments given to another. This is dyarchy. Indians handled minor subjects while British retained major control.\n________________________________________\nLegislative Powers under 1919 Act\nThe Act expanded legislative powers. Members could ask questions, discuss budget, and introduce resolutions. Franchise was extended to more people. However, voting rights were limited. Property and educational qualifications were required to vote. Therefore, only a small portion of population could participate.\nThe Governor-General retained overriding authority. He could veto laws and certify bills. He also had ordinance power. Thus, executive authority remained dominant.\n________________________________________\nProvincial Autonomy (Limited Form)\nThough full provincial autonomy was not introduced, the Act laid foundation for it. Provinces received some powers. Legislative councils were expanded. Indian ministers handled transferred subjects. This gradually prepared provinces for responsible government.\n________________________________________\nDefects of Dyarchy\nDyarchy created administrative confusion. Ministers handled transferred subjects but lacked financial control. Reserved subjects controlled finance and police. Therefore, ministers could not implement policies effectively. Governors retained overriding powers. This limited responsible government.\nAnother defect was division of authority. Coordination between reserved and transferred subjects was difficult. This led to inefficiency. As a result, dyarchy failed in practice.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nGovernment of India Act 1919 introduced:\n\u2022 Bicameral legislature at centre \n\u2022 Dyarchy in provinces \n\u2022 Limited responsible government \n\u2022 Expanded legislative councils \n\u2022 Increased Indian participation \n\u2022 Extended franchise \nThis Act marked transition toward responsible government.\n________________________________________\nHistorical Significance\nThe Government of India Act 1919 is important because:\n\u2022 It introduced responsible government (partial) \n\u2022 It introduced dyarchy \n\u2022 It created bicameral legislature \n\u2022 It increased political participation \n\u2022 It prepared ground for 1935 Act \nThis Act was an important step in constitutional evolution leading to federal system later.\n________________________________________\nBackground of Government of India Act, 1935\nThe Government of India Act 1919 introduced dyarchy in provinces, but the system failed due to administrative confusion and limited powers given to Indian ministers. Indian leaders demanded responsible government and greater autonomy. The Simon Commission (1927), Round Table Conferences, and constitutional negotiations led to the enactment of the Government of India Act 1935. This Act was the most comprehensive constitutional legislation before independence. Many provisions of the present Constitution are based on this Act.\nThe Government of India Act 1935 introduced federal structure, provincial autonomy, division of powers, bicameral legislature, federal court, and emergency provisions. It was the longest Act passed by British Parliament for India.\n________________________________________\nFederal Scheme under Government of India Act 1935\nThe Act proposed the establishment of an All-India Federation consisting of British Indian provinces and princely states. The federation was voluntary for princely states. Provinces were automatically included, but princely states had the option to join. Since princely states did not join, the federation never came into existence. However, the idea of federalism influenced the later Constitution.\nThe Act divided legislative powers into three lists:\n\u2022 Federal List \n\u2022 Provincial List \n\u2022 Concurrent List \nThe Federal List included subjects such as defence, foreign affairs, and currency. The Provincial List included police, public order, and local government. The Concurrent List included subjects where both centre and provinces could legislate. This division later became the basis of the Seventh Schedule of the Constitution.\nThe Act also introduced residuary powers. These powers were given to the Governor-General. This showed strong central control.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nFederal List \u2192 Centre\nProvincial List \u2192 Provinces\nConcurrent List \u2192 Both\nThis system is similar to present Constitution.\n________________________________________\nProvincial Autonomy\nThe Government of India Act 1935 abolished dyarchy in provinces and introduced provincial autonomy. Provinces were given independent authority. Provincial governments were made responsible to legislative councils. Ministers were appointed from elected members. This introduced responsible government at provincial level.\nGovernors, however, retained special powers. They could override ministers in certain matters. They also controlled finance and law and order in emergencies. Thus, autonomy was limited but significant.\nProvincial autonomy allowed Indian leaders to form governments. Elections were conducted in 1937. Congress formed ministries in several provinces. This was the first experience of responsible governance.\n________________________________________\nExample\nAfter 1937 elections:\nCongress formed government in provinces like Madras and Bombay.\nMinisters handled administration.\nThis was beginning of responsible government.\n________________________________________\nDyarchy at the Centre\nWhile dyarchy was abolished in provinces, it was introduced at the centre. Federal subjects were divided into reserved and transferred subjects. Reserved subjects were controlled by Governor-General. Transferred subjects were handled by ministers responsible to legislature.\nHowever, since federation never came into existence, dyarchy at centre was not implemented. Still, it showed gradual movement toward responsible government.\n________________________________________\nBicameral Legislature\nThe Act introduced bicameral legislature in some provinces. At the centre also, two houses were proposed:\n\u2022 Federal Assembly \n\u2022 Council of States \nThis influenced present parliamentary structure.\n________________________________________\nFederal Court\nThe Government of India Act 1935 established the Federal Court in 1937. The court resolved disputes between centre and provinces. It also interpreted constitutional provisions. This was the beginning of constitutional adjudication in India.\nThe Federal Court later became foundation for the Supreme Court of India. It introduced judicial review and constitutional interpretation.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nFederal Court role:\nCentre vs Province dispute \u2192 Federal Court decides\nInterpretation of law \u2192 Federal Court\nThis resembles present Supreme Court.\n________________________________________\nOther Important Features\nThe Government of India Act 1935 also introduced:\n\u2022 Public Service Commission \n\u2022 Reserve Bank of India \n\u2022 Federal Railway Authority \n\u2022 Emergency provisions \n\u2022 Separation of powers \nThese features influenced the Constitution.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nGovernment of India Act 1935 introduced:\n\u2022 Federal structure \n\u2022 Provincial autonomy \n\u2022 Division of powers \n\u2022 Bicameral legislature \n\u2022 Federal court \n\u2022 Responsible government in provinces \n\u2022 Emergency provisions \nThis Act became the backbone of the Constitution.\n________________________________________\nFederal Court of India (1937)\nThe Government of India Act 1935 provided for the establishment of a Federal Court. Accordingly, the Federal Court of India was established in 1937. This was the first constitutional court in India. Before this, judicial appeals from India went directly to the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council in England. The Federal Court created a domestic constitutional adjudication system.\nThe Federal Court consisted of a Chief Justice and other judges appointed by the British Crown. The court had original jurisdiction, appellate jurisdiction, and advisory jurisdiction. It could decide disputes between provinces and centre. It also interpreted constitutional provisions under the Government of India Act 1935.\nThe establishment of the Federal Court introduced the concept of constitutional interpretation. The court ensured that authorities acted within their powers. This marked the beginning of constitutional supremacy and judicial review in India. Though appeals could still be made to the Privy Council, the Federal Court played a crucial role in shaping constitutional jurisprudence.\nThe Federal Court also clarified distribution of legislative powers. It interpreted federal, provincial, and concurrent lists. This strengthened federal governance. Many principles developed by the Federal Court later influenced the Supreme Court.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nIf centre passes law beyond its powers \u2192 Federal Court decides validity\nIf province disputes centre \u2192 Federal Court resolves dispute\nThis is similar to present Supreme Court function.\n________________________________________\nHistorical Importance\nFederal Court introduced:\n\u2022 Constitutional interpretation \n\u2022 Federal dispute resolution \n\u2022 Judicial review \n\u2022 Constitutional supremacy \n\u2022 Independent judiciary concept \nThe Federal Court later became the foundation for the Supreme Court of India.\n________________________________________\nIndian Independence Act, 1947\nThe Indian Independence Act 1947 marked the end of British rule in India. This Act created two independent dominions \u2014 India and Pakistan. The Act came into force on August 15, 1947. It transferred power from British government to Indian leaders. This Act laid the foundation for framing the Constitution.\nOne of the most important features of the Act was partition of India. British India was divided into two dominions. Each dominion had power to frame its own constitution. The British Parliament no longer had authority over India. This marked complete legislative sovereignty.\nThe Act abolished the office of Secretary of State for India. The British government ended its administrative control. The Governor-General became constitutional head representing the Crown but acted on advice of Indian ministers. Thus, real power transferred to Indian leadership.\nAnother important feature was that princely states were given freedom to join India or Pakistan. British suzerainty over princely states ended. States could accede to either dominion. This led to integration of princely states into India.\nThe Indian Independence Act 1947 also gave power to the Constituent Assembly to frame the Constitution. The Assembly became sovereign legislative body. It could make laws and draft Constitution.\nThe Act also ended the applicability of Government of India Act 1935, except as interim Constitution. Until the new Constitution was adopted, India functioned under modified 1935 Act.\n________________________________________\nExample\nAfter independence:\nIndian leaders made laws\nBritish Parliament had no authority\nConstituent Assembly framed Constitution\nThis shows legislative sovereignty.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nBefore 1947:\nBritish Parliament \u2192 Supreme authority\nAfter 1947:\nIndian Constituent Assembly \u2192 Supreme authority\nThis marks independence.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nIndian Independence Act 1947:\n\u2022 Ended British rule \n\u2022 Created India and Pakistan \n\u2022 Gave legislative sovereignty \n\u2022 Abolished Secretary of State \n\u2022 Allowed princely states accession \n\u2022 Empowered Constituent Assembly \n\u2022 Prepared ground for Constitution \nThis Act marks transition from colonial rule to independent constitutional governance.\n________________________________________\nFormation of Constituent Assembly\nAfter the Indian Independence Act 1947, the most important task before Indian leaders was to frame a Constitution for independent India. The idea of a Constituent Assembly was first proposed by M.N. Roy in 1934. Later, the Indian National Congress demanded a constitution framed by Indians themselves. The British government accepted this demand through the Cabinet Mission Plan of 1946. Accordingly, the Constituent Assembly was formed to draft the Constitution.\nThe Constituent Assembly was not directly elected by the people. Members were elected indirectly by provincial legislative assemblies. Seats were distributed among provinces based on population. Representatives of princely states were nominated by rulers. The Constituent Assembly first met on 9 December 1946. Dr. Sachchidananda Sinha served as temporary chairman. Later, Dr. Rajendra Prasad was elected as permanent President of the Assembly.\nInitially, the Constituent Assembly had 389 members. After partition, membership reduced to 299. Out of these, 229 represented provinces and 70 represented princely states. The Assembly included lawyers, scholars, administrators, and political leaders. This ensured diverse representation.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nTotal members before partition \u2192 389\nAfter partition \u2192 299\nProvinces \u2192 229\nPrincely states \u2192 70\nThis shows composition of Assembly.\n________________________________________\nWorking of Constituent Assembly\nThe Constituent Assembly performed two major functions. First, it framed the Constitution. Second, it functioned as legislative body. After independence, the Assembly also acted as provisional parliament. It passed laws and discussed national issues.\nThe Assembly worked through debates and discussions. Members discussed each provision in detail. Draft Constitution was examined clause by clause. Amendments were proposed and debated. This democratic process ensured careful drafting.\nThe Assembly took 2 years, 11 months, and 18 days to complete the Constitution. It held 11 sessions and 165 meetings. The Constitution was adopted on 26 November 1949. It came into force on 26 January 1950.\n________________________________________\nCommittees of Constituent Assembly\nTo simplify drafting work, the Constituent Assembly formed several committees. These committees examined different aspects of the Constitution. The committees submitted reports which were discussed by the Assembly.\nMajor committees included:\n\u2022 Union Powers Committee \n\u2022 Union Constitution Committee \n\u2022 Provincial Constitution Committee \n\u2022 Advisory Committee on Fundamental Rights \n\u2022 Drafting Committee \n\u2022 Steering Committee \n\u2022 Rules Committee \nEach committee handled specific constitutional matters. This helped in systematic drafting.\nFor example, the Advisory Committee examined fundamental rights and minority protections. The Union Powers Committee determined distribution of powers. The Drafting Committee prepared the final draft.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nCommittee system worked like:\nCommittees \u2192 prepare report\nAssembly \u2192 debate report\nAssembly \u2192 adopt provisions\nThis ensured detailed drafting.\n________________________________________\nDrafting Committee\nThe Drafting Committee was the most important committee of the Constituent Assembly. It was appointed on 29 August 1947. Dr. B.R. Ambedkar was appointed Chairman of the Drafting Committee. Other members included K.M. Munshi, Alladi Krishnaswamy Ayyar, N. Gopalaswami Ayyangar, B.L. Mitter, Mohammad Saadulla, and D.P. Khaitan.\nThe Drafting Committee prepared the draft Constitution based on reports of other committees. It examined constitutional provisions from various countries. The committee refined language and structure. Dr. Ambedkar played a major role in drafting.\nThe Draft Constitution was published in 1948. Members of the Assembly discussed it clause by clause. Amendments were introduced and debated. The Drafting Committee revised the document accordingly.\nThe Drafting Committee ensured that the Constitution included federal structure, fundamental rights, independent judiciary, and parliamentary system. The committee balanced flexibility and rigidity. It also ensured protection of minorities and social justice.\n________________________________________\nExample\nDraft prepared \u2192 Assembly debates \u2192 amendments proposed \u2192 Drafting Committee revises\nThis process continued until final adoption.\n________________________________________\nImportance of Constituent Assembly\nThe Constituent Assembly played a historic role. It framed a Constitution suited to Indian conditions. It adopted democratic principles and federal structure. It ensured protection of fundamental rights. It established independent judiciary.\nThe Assembly also ensured representation of different communities. Members debated issues openly. The Constitution reflected collective wisdom.\nThe Constituent Assembly finally adopted the Constitution on 26 November 1949. It came into force on 26 January 1950, creating the Republic of India under the Constitution of India.\n________________________________________\nObjective Resolution\nThe Objective Resolution played a crucial role in framing the Constitution. It was moved by Jawaharlal Nehru in the Constituent Assembly on 13 December 1946. This resolution laid down the philosophy and guiding principles of the Constitution. It declared that India would become an independent sovereign republic. It also emphasized justice, equality, liberty, and fundamental rights.\nThe Objective Resolution stated that power and authority of the government would be derived from the people. It also declared that India would be a federation of states. The resolution emphasized safeguarding minorities, backward classes, and tribal communities. It also aimed to promote international peace and cooperation.\nThis resolution later became the basis of the Preamble of the Constitution. The ideals of sovereignty, democracy, republic, justice, liberty, and equality were derived from this resolution. Thus, the Objective Resolution guided the drafting process.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nObjective Resolution \u2192 Principles\nPrinciples \u2192 Draft Constitution\nDraft Constitution \u2192 Final Constitution\nThis shows its importance.\n________________________________________\nMaking of the Constitution\nThe making of the Constitution involved detailed debates and discussions. After the Drafting Committee prepared the draft, it was placed before the Constituent Assembly. Members discussed each article. Amendments were proposed and debated. The Assembly considered thousands of amendments.\nThe Constitution was prepared after examining various constitutional systems. The framers borrowed useful features from different countries. Parliamentary system was adopted from Britain. Fundamental rights were inspired by USA. Directive principles were borrowed from Ireland. Federal structure was influenced by Canada. This comparative approach ensured a balanced Constitution.\nThe Constituent Assembly carefully debated issues such as federalism, fundamental rights, judiciary, and executive powers. Members expressed different opinions. These debates helped refine the Constitution.\nThe drafting process took nearly three years. The Assembly met for 11 sessions. It held extensive discussions. The Constitution emerged as a comprehensive document.\n________________________________________\nExample\nMembers debated:\n\u2022 Should India be federal or unitary? \n\u2022 Should judiciary be independent? \n\u2022 Should fundamental rights be enforceable? \nThese debates shaped the Constitution.\n________________________________________\nAdoption of the Constitution\nThe Constitution was finally adopted by the Constituent Assembly on 26 November 1949. On this date, members signed the document. This marked completion of drafting process. However, not all provisions came into force immediately.\nSome provisions relating to citizenship, elections, and provisional parliament came into force immediately. The remaining provisions came into force on 26 January 1950. This date was chosen to commemorate the declaration of Purna Swaraj in 1930.\nThe adoption of the Constitution marked the end of colonial constitutional framework. The Government of India Act 1935 ceased to operate. India became a constitutional democracy.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nAdoption date \u2192 26 November 1949\nEnforcement date \u2192 26 January 1950\nThis shows difference between adoption and enforcement.\n________________________________________\nEnforcement of the Constitution\nThe Constitution came into force on 26 January 1950. On this day, India became a Republic. The office of Governor-General was replaced by President. The Constituent Assembly became provisional parliament. Democratic governance began.\nThe enforcement of the Constitution established parliamentary democracy. It introduced fundamental rights, directive principles, and federal structure. The Constitution became supreme law of the land.\nThe Constitution created three organs of government:\n\u2022 Legislature \n\u2022 Executive \n\u2022 Judiciary \nIt also established rule of law and constitutional supremacy. All authorities became subject to the Constitution.\n________________________________________\nConceptual Importance\nObjective Resolution \u2192 Philosophy of Constitution\nMaking of Constitution \u2192 Drafting process\nAdoption \u2192 Final approval\nEnforcement \u2192 Constitution came into force\nThese stages completed constitutional development.\n________________________________________\nSources of the Indian Constitution\nThe framers of the Constitution of India did not create the Constitution in isolation. They examined constitutions of various countries and adopted features suitable for Indian conditions. The Indian Constitution is therefore a combination of many constitutional traditions. However, borrowed features were modified to suit Indian society and governance.\nOne of the most important sources of the Indian Constitution was the Government of India Act 1935. Many administrative provisions were taken from this Act. These included federal structure, office of Governor, emergency provisions, public service commission, and administrative framework. The division of powers between centre and states was also based on the 1935 Act.\nThe British Constitution influenced the parliamentary system in India. The concepts of cabinet government, collective responsibility, rule of law, and legislative procedure were adopted from Britain. The Indian Constitution also adopted the idea of nominal executive and real executive. The President acts as constitutional head similar to the British monarch.\nThe Constitution of the United States influenced fundamental rights, judicial review, and independent judiciary. The concept of written constitution and supremacy of constitution were also inspired by USA. The procedure for removal of judges was also borrowed.\nThe Constitution of Ireland influenced directive principles of state policy. These principles guide governance and promote social welfare. The idea of socio-economic justice came from Irish Constitution.\nThe Canadian Constitution influenced federal structure with strong centre. Residuary powers were given to centre. This ensured unity and strong national government.\nThe Australian Constitution influenced concurrent list and trade and commerce provisions. The idea of freedom of trade within the country was borrowed.\nThe South African Constitution influenced amendment procedure. The method of electing members of Rajya Sabha was also borrowed.\nThe Constitution of Japan influenced the concept of procedure established by law under Article 21.\nThus, the Indian Constitution combined features from multiple sources. However, it remains unique due to its comprehensive nature.\n________________________________________\nIllustration\nBritain \u2192 Parliamentary system\nUSA \u2192 Fundamental rights\nIreland \u2192 Directive principles\nCanada \u2192 Federal structure\nAustralia \u2192 Concurrent list\nSouth Africa \u2192 Amendment procedure\nThis shows sources.\n________________________________________\nBorrowed Features Explained\nThe parliamentary system adopted from Britain means executive is responsible to legislature. The Council of Ministers is collectively responsible to Lok Sabha. This ensures democratic accountability.\nFundamental rights borrowed from USA protect individual liberty. These rights are enforceable in courts. Judicial review ensures protection.\nDirective principles borrowed from Ireland promote welfare state. These principles guide government policies.\nFederal structure borrowed from Canada ensures division of powers. Centre and states have separate authority.\nThus, borrowed features were integrated into Indian framework.\n________________________________________\nNature of the Indian Constitution (Evolutionary Perspective)\nThe Indian Constitution reflects historical evolution. It combines federal and unitary features. It provides parliamentary democracy. It ensures fundamental rights. It establishes independent judiciary.\nThe Constitution is partly rigid and partly flexible. Some provisions require special majority for amendment. Others can be amended by simple majority. This balance ensures stability and adaptability.\nThe Constitution also establishes rule of law. All authorities derive power from Constitution. No authority is above law. Judicial review ensures constitutional supremacy.\nThe Constitution also promotes social justice. Directive principles guide welfare policies. Fundamental rights protect individuals. This balance ensures democratic governance.\n________________________________________\nTransition from Colonial Rule to Republic\nThe adoption of the Constitution marked transition from colonial rule to republican governance. Before 1950, India was governed under British Crown. After enforcement, India became sovereign republic. The President replaced Governor-General. Sovereignty shifted to people.\nThe Constitution established democratic institutions. Elections were introduced. Legislature became representative body. Executive became responsible to legislature. Judiciary became independent.\nThe Constitution also unified India. Princely states were integrated. Federal structure created unity with diversity. Fundamental rights ensured equality.\nThus, the Constitution transformed India into democratic republic.\n________________________________________\nOverall Conclusion of Unit 1\nThe Indian Constitution is the result of gradual constitutional evolution. Beginning with East India Company rule, British Parliament introduced various reforms. Each Act contributed to constitutional development. The Government of India Act 1935 provided structural framework. The Indian Independence Act 1947 granted sovereignty. The Constituent Assembly drafted the Constitution. Borrowed features enriched the document.\nThus, the Constitution reflects historical experience, democratic ideals, and constitutional wisdom. Unit 1 explains this entire evolution from colonial governance to modern constitutional democracy.\n"),null,a8,a9),$async$jH)
