s($,"b0k","aJK",()=>A.b([A.fM("The first law by British Parliament to regulate the Company. Key features:\n\u2022 Created post of Governor-General of Bengal (Warren Hastings \u2013 first holder)\n\u2022 Established the Supreme Court at Calcutta (1774)\n\u2022 Created Executive Council of 4 members\n\u2022 Prohibited officials from private trade\n\u2022 Introduced parliamentary supervision","What was the Regulating Act of 1773 and its key features?","fc1_01"),A.fM("Nand Kumar accused Warren Hastings of corruption. He was then tried by the Supreme Court for forgery (under English law) and sentenced to death.\n\nSignificance: Exposed the jurisdictional clash between the Supreme Court and the executive under the Regulating Act, highlighting the need for clearer separation of powers.","What was the Nand Kumar Case (1775) and its significance?","fc1_02"),A.fM("Pitt's India Act created a Board of Control consisting of British government officials.\n\n\u2022 Board of Control \u2192 supervised political affairs\n\u2022 Court of Directors \u2192 managed commercial activities\n\nThis dual structure meant: Political authority = British govt | Commercial authority = Company",'What is "Dual Control" introduced by Pitt\'s India Act, 1784?',"fc1_03"),A.fM("\u2022 Abolished the Company's monopoly over trade with India (Company retained monopoly only over China trade and tea)\n\u2022 Allocated \u20b91 lakh per year for education in India (first state education responsibility)\n\u2022 Allowed Christian missionaries to enter India\n\u2022 Affirmed Crown sovereignty over Indian territories","What did the Charter Act of 1813 introduce?","fc1_04"),A.fM("\u2022 Made Governor-General of Bengal \u2192 Governor-General of INDIA (Lord William Bentinck was first)\n\u2022 Gave the Governor-General complete legislative authority over all of India\n\u2022 Abolished Company's commercial activities \u2013 became purely administrative\n\u2022 Created the post of Law Member (Macaulay \u2013 Led codification of Indian Penal Code)\n\u2022 Introduced concept of open civil services","Why is the Charter Act of 1833 the most important pre-independence Act?","fc1_05"),A.fM("Dyarchy = dual government in provinces.\n\nSubjects were divided into:\n\u2022 Reserved Subjects \u2192 Governor (Police, Finance, Revenue, Law & Order)\n\u2022 Transferred Subjects \u2192 Indian Ministers answerable to legislature (Education, Health, Agriculture)\n\nDyarchy failed because ministers lacked financial control over reserved departments.","What is Dyarchy as introduced in the Government of India Act 1919?","fc1_06"),A.fM("\u2022 Federal List \u2192 Centre (Defence, Foreign Affairs, Currency)\n\u2022 Provincial List \u2192 Provinces (Police, Public Order, Local Govt)\n\u2022 Concurrent List \u2192 Both Centre and Provinces\n\nThis 3-list division became the basis for the 7th Schedule of the Indian Constitution.","What are the 3 lists in the Government of India Act 1935?","fc1_07"),A.fM("Formed as per the Cabinet Mission Plan of 1946.\n\nComposition:\n\u2022 Before partition: 389 members\n\u2022 After partition: 299 members (229 Provinces + 70 Princely States)\n\u2022 Indirectly elected by provincial legislative assemblies\n\u2022 First met: 9 December 1946\n\u2022 Temporary Chairman: Dr. Sachchidananda Sinha\n\u2022 President: Dr. Rajendra Prasad","How was the Constituent Assembly formed and what was its composition?","fc1_08"),A.fM("Moved by Jawaharlal Nehru on 13 December 1946.\n\nDeclared India would be:\n\u2022 Independent Sovereign Republic\n\u2022 A federation of states\n\u2022 Guaranteeing justice, liberty, equality, and fundamental rights\n\u2022 Protecting minorities, backward classes, tribal communities\n\nBecame the foundation for the PREAMBLE of the Constitution.","What is the Objective Resolution and why does it matter?","fc1_09"),A.fM('\ud83c\uddec\ud83c\udde7 UK \u2192 Parliamentary system, Cabinet responsibility, Rule of Law\n\ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf8 USA \u2192 Fundamental Rights, Judicial Review, Written Constitution\n\ud83c\uddee\ud83c\uddea Ireland \u2192 Directive Principles of State Policy\n\ud83c\udde8\ud83c\udde6 Canada \u2192 Federal structure with strong Centre\n\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddfa Australia \u2192 Concurrent List\n\ud83c\uddff\ud83c\udde6 South Africa \u2192 Amendment procedure\n\ud83c\uddef\ud83c\uddf5 Japan \u2192 "Procedure established by law" (Article 21)',"Which countries influenced the Indian Constitution and what did India borrow?","fc1_10"),A.fM("Context: Related to Indian Councils Act.\n\nIssue: Delegation of legislative power.\n\nJudgment: Legislative power can be delegated under limits.\n\nSignificance: Established the concept of DELEGATED LEGISLATION in India.","\ud83e\udde0 Case Law: Queen v Burah (1878)","fc1_11"),A.fM("Issue: Extent of delegated legislation.\n\nJudgment: Delegation is allowed, but ESSENTIAL LEGISLATIVE FUNCTIONS cannot be delegated to the executive.\n\nSignificance: Clarified the limits of law-making power distribution derived from colonial practices.","\ud83e\udde0 In re Delhi Laws Act Case (1951)","fc1_12"),A.fM("Judgment: Introduced the BASIC STRUCTURE DOCTRINE.\n\nSignificance: Protects features like Federalism, Democracy, and Judicial Review from being destroyed by amendments. These features evolved from the historical Acts studied in Unit 1.","\ud83e\udde0 Kesavananda Bharati v State of Kerala (1973)","fc1_13"),A.fM("Context: Balance between Fundamental Rights (FR) and Directive Principles (DPSP).\n\nSignificance: Shows the evolution of the Constitution from historical roots toward limited government and protection of individual rights.","\ud83e\udde0 Minerva Mills v Union of India (1980)","fc1_14"),A.fM("Context: Federal structure and distribution of powers (influenced by 1935 Act).\n\nJudgment: The Centre is not subordinate to the states; India has a strong central government.\n\nSignificance: Reflects the strong-centre model established by the 1935 Act.","\ud83e\udde0 State of West Bengal v Union of India (1963)","fc1_15")],t.x7))
